{{Infobox language |name=Greek Sign Language |states=[[Greece]] |speakers=Estimates run from 6,000 to 60,000 |date=2014 |ref=e18 |speakers2=Differences may reflect degree of fluency. |familycolor=Sign |fam1=[[French Sign Language family|French Sign]] |fam2=[[French Sign Language|FSL]]–[[ASL]] mix |iso3=gss |glotto=gree1271 |glottorefname=Greek Sign Language }} '''Greek Sign Language''' ({{lang-el|[[:el:Ελληνική νοηματική γλώσσα|Ελληνική νοηματική γλώσσα]]}}) is the [[sign language]] of the [[Greece|Greek]] [[deaf]] community. It has been [[Legal recognition of sign languages|legally recognised]] as the official language of the Deaf Community in Greece by Law 2817 in 2000.
The Greek Sign Language is estimated to be used by about 40,600 signers in 1986.<ref> {{cite web | title=An Environment for Deaf Accessibility to Educational Content | url=http://www.esstt.rnu.tn/utic/tica2007/sys_files/medias/docs/p23.pdf | accessdate=2010-03-18 | author=Eleni Efthimiou |author2=Stavroula-Evita Fotinea | work=Proceedings of the First International Conference in Information and Communication Technology & Accessibility April 12 – 14, 2007, Hammamet – TUNISIA | publisher=Mohamed JEMNI (editor) | location=Tynisia }} </ref>
Greek SL formed in the 1950s when [[American Sign Language]] and [[French Sign Language]] came together, with admixture from indigenous sign.
