{{Culture of the United States}} 
The [[United States|United States of America]] has a [[Race (human categorization)|racially]] and [[ethnic group|ethnically]] [[Multiethnic society|diverse]] population.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.census.gov/population/pop-profile/2000/chap16.pdf |title=OUR DIVERSE POPULATION: Race and Hispanic Origin, 2000 |accessdate=April 16, 2005 |format=PDF |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]}}</ref> The [[United States Census]] officially recognizes six [[Race and ethnicity in the United States Census|racial categories]]: [[White Americans|White American]], Black or [[African Americans|African American]], [[Native Americans in the United States|American Indian]] and [[Alaska Natives|Alaska Native]], [[Asian Americans|Asian American]], [[Native Hawaiians|Native Hawaiian]] and [[Pacific Islands Americans|Other Pacific Islander]], and people of two or more races; a category called "some other race" is also used in the census and other surveys, but is not official.<ref name="Standards" /><ref name="Overview" /><ref name=PEPT3race08>{{cite web |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/DTTable?_bm=y&-state=dt&-context=dt&-ds_name=PEP_2008_EST&-CONTEXT=dt&-mt_name=PEP_2008_EST_G2008_T003_2008&-tree_id=809&-redoLog=false&-currentselections=PEP_2006_EST_G2006_T004_2006&-geo_id=01000US&-geo_id=02000US1&-geo_id=02000US2&-geo_id=02000US3&-geo_id=02000US4&-search_results=01000US&-format=&-_lang=en |title=Detailed Tables – American FactFinder; T3-2008. Race - 7|work=2008 Population Estimates |publisher=U.S. Census Bureau I |accessdate=February 28, 2010}}</ref> The United States Census Bureau also classifies Americans as "Hispanic or Latino" and "Not Hispanic or Latino", which identifies [[Hispanic and Latino Americans]] as an [[Race and ethnicity in the United States Census|''ethnicity'']] (not a ''race'') distinct from others, and comprising the largest minority group in the nation.<ref name="Standards" /><ref name="Overview" /><ref name=PEPT4HL>{{cite web |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/DTTable?_bm=y&-state=dt&-context=dt&-ds_name=PEP_2008_EST&-CONTEXT=dt&-mt_name=PEP_2008_EST_G2008_T004_2008&-tree_id=809&-redoLog=false&-currentselections=PEP_2006_EST_G2006_T004_2006&-geo_id=01000US&-geo_id=02000US1&-geo_id=02000US2&-geo_id=02000US3&-geo_id=02000US4&-search_results=01000US&-format=&-_lang=en |title=Detailed Tables – American FactFinder; T4-2008. Hispanic or Latino By Race. 15 |work=2008 Population Estimates |publisher=U.S. Census Bureau |accessdate=February 28, 2010}}</ref>

The United States Supreme Court unanimously held that "race" is not limited to Census designations on the "race question" but extends to all ethnicities, and thus can include Jewish and Arab as well as Polish or Italian or Irish, etc.<ref>St. Francis Coll. v. Al-Khazraji 481 U.S. 604 (1987), Shaare Tefila Congregation v. Cobb, 481 U.S. 615 (1987).</ref> In fact, the Census asks an "Ancestry Question" which covers the broader notion of ethnicity initially in the 2000 Census long form and now in the American Community Survey. The ancestry question will return in the 2020 Census.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/02/01/582338628/-what-kind-of-white-2020-census-to-ask-white-people-about-origins|title=2020 Census Will Ask White People More About Their Ethnicities|work=NPR.org|access-date=2018-02-09|language=en}}</ref>

{{As of|July 2016}}, White Americans are the racial majority. <!-- Please do not "fix" the following sentence. In the U.S., African Americans are considered a *racial* minority and Latinos are an *ethnic* minority. --> African Americans are the largest racial minority, amounting to an estimated 12.7% of the population. Hispanic and Latino Americans amount to an estimated 17.8% of the total U.S. population, making up the largest ethnic minority.<ref name="auto">{{Cite web|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=ACS_16_1YR_CP05&prodType=table|title=2016 American Community Survey 1-Year Estimates|last=|first=|date=|publisher=American Community Survey|website=U.S. Census Fact Finder|accessdate=February 19, 2018}}</ref> The [[non-Hispanic whites|White, non-Hispanic or Latino population]] make up 61.3% of the nation's total, with the total White population (including White Hispanics and Latinos) being 76.9%.<ref>{{cite web |title=Quick Facts – Race and Hispanic Origin |url=https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/fact/table/US/PST045216 |publisher=United States Census Bureau |accessdate=August 8, 2017 }}</ref>

White Americans are the majority in every census-defined region (Northeast, Midwest, South, West) and in every state except [[Hawaii]],<ref name="auto"/> but contribute the highest proportion of the population in the [[Midwestern United States]], at 85% per the [[Population Estimates Program]] (PEP),<ref name=PEPT3race08 /> or 83% per the [[American Community Survey]] (ACS).<ref name=b02001>{{cite web |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/DTTable?_bm=y&-context=dt&-ds_name=ACS_2008_1YR_G00_&-mt_name=ACS_2008_1YR_G2000_B02001&-CONTEXT=dt&-tree_id=306&-redoLog=true&-currentselections=ACS_2006_EST_G2000_B02001&-currentselections=ACS_2006_EST_G2000_B02003&-currentselections=ACS_2006_EST_G2000_C02003&-geo_id=01000US&-geo_id=02000US1&-geo_id=02000US2&-geo_id=02000US3&-geo_id=02000US4&-search_results=01000US&-format=&-_lang=en |title=B02001. RACE – Universe: TOTAL POPULATION |work= 2008 American Community Survey 1-Year Estimates |accessdate=February 28, 2010 |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]}}</ref>{{Verify source|date=May 2014}} Non-Hispanic Whites make up 79% of the Midwest's population, the highest ratio of any region.<ref name=PEPT4HL /> However, 35% of White Americans (whether all White Americans or non-Hispanic/Latino only) live in [[Southern United States|the South]], the most of any region.<ref name=PEPT3race08 /><ref name=PEPT4HL />

55% of the African American population lives in the South.<ref name=PEPT3race08 /> A plurality or majority of the other official groups reside in [[Western United States|the West]]. The latter region is home to 42% of Hispanic and Latino Americans, 46% of [[Asian Americans]], 48% of [[Native Americans in the United States|American Indians]] and [[Alaska Natives]], 68% of [[Native Hawaiians]] and [[Pacific Islands Americans|Other Pacific Islanders]], 37% of the "two or more races" population ([[Multiracial Americans]]), and 46% of those self-designated as "some other race".<ref name=PEPT3race08 /><ref name=b03002regions>{{cite web |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/DTTable?_bm=y&-context=dt&-ds_name=ACS_2008_1YR_G00_&-mt_name=ACS_2008_1YR_G2000_B03002&-CONTEXT=dt&-tree_id=306&-redoLog=true&-geo_id=01000US&-geo_id=02000US1&-geo_id=02000US2&-geo_id=02000US3&-geo_id=02000US4&-search_results=ALL&-format=&-_lang=en |title=B03002. HISPANIC OR LATINO ORIGIN BY RACE – Universe: TOTAL POPULATION by region|work=2008 American Community Survey 1-Year Estimates |accessdate=March 1, 2010 |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]}}</ref>

