{{Infobox language |name=Seki |altname=Sekiyani |states=[[Equatorial Guinea]], [[Gabon]] |speakers=12,000 |date=2001-2007 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Niger-Congo |fam2=[[Atlantic–Congo languages|Atlantic–Congo]] |fam3=[[Benue–Congo languages|Benue–Congo]] |fam4=[[Bantoid languages|Bantoid]] |fam5=[[Bantu languages|Bantu]] ([[Guthrie classification of Bantu languages#Zone B|Zone B]]) |fam6=[[Kele languages|Kele]] (B.20) ? |iso3=syi |glotto=seki1238 |glottorefname=Seki |guthrie=B.21 |map=Idioma seki.png }}
'''Seki''', also '''Baseke''', '''Sheke''' or '''Sekiana''', is a language indigenous to [[Equatorial Guinea]] and [[Gabon]]. It had been spoken in villages of [[Rio Campo]] and [[Northern Bata]], along the coast, but its native speakers have begun abandoning the language for [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[Fang language|Fang]], and [[Kombe language|Kombe]].
